{"id":"2101.04050","submitter":"Miguel M. Ugeda","authors":"Wen Wan, Paul Dreher, Daniel Mu\\~noz-Segovia, Rishav Harsh, Haojie\n  Guo, Antonio J. Martinez-Galera, Francisco Guinea, Fernando de Juan and\n  Miguel M. Ugeda","title":"Observation of superconducting collective modes from competing pairing\n  instabilities in single-layer NbSe$_2$","comments":"Advanced Materials (2022)","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1002/adma.202206078","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con cond-mat.mes-hall cond-mat.mtrl-sci cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In certain unconventional superconductors with sizable electronic\ncorrelations, the availability of closely competing pairing channels leads to\ncharacteristic soft collective fluctuations of the order parameters, which\nleave fingerprints in many observables and allow to scrutinize the phase\ncompetition. Superconducting layered materials, where electron-electron\ninteractions are enhanced with decreasing thickness, are promising candidates\nto display these correlation effects. In this work, we report the existence of\na soft collective mode in single-layer NbSe$_2$, observed as a characteristic\nresonance excitation in high resolution tunneling spectra. This resonance is\nobserved along with higher harmonics, its frequency $\\Omega/2\\Delta$ is\nanticorrelated with the local superconducting gap $\\Delta$, and its amplitude\ngradually vanishes by increasing the temperature and upon applying a magnetic\nfield up to the critical values (T$_C$ and H$_{C2}$), which sets an unambiguous\nlink to the superconducting state. Aided by a microscopic model that captures\nthe main experimental observations, we interpret this resonance as a collective\nLeggett mode that represents the fluctuation towards a proximate f-wave triplet\nstate, due to subleading attraction in the triplet channel. Our findings\ndemonstrate the fundamental role of correlations in superconducting 2D\ntransition metal dichalcogenides, opening a path towards unconventional\nsuperconductivity in simple, scalable and transferable 2D superconductors.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 11 Jan 2021 17:37:17 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 15 Sep 2021 14:52:50 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 4 Jul 2022 20:41:49 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 30 Aug 2022 14:12:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-31"}
